05344nam a22008175i 9780812297997DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122979977 a10.9783/97808122979972doi  a(DE-B1597)573125  a(OCoLC)1257324331  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBS580.D3bK36 2021eb 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a222/.40922231 aKarras, Ruth Mazo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThou Art the Man :bThe Masculinity of David in the Christian and Jewish Middle Ages /cRuth Mazo Karras. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b28 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Middle Ages Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. David His Tens of Thousands: Prowess and Piety -- tChapter 2. Surpassing the Love of Women: Love, Friendship, Loyalty Between Men -- tChapter 3. I Have Sinned Against the Lord: Sex and Penitenc -- tChapter 4. With Sacred Music upon the Harp: Creativity and Ecstasy -- tChapter 5. O My Son Absalom: Establishing a Dynasty -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"How do we approach the study of masculinity in the past?" Ruth Mazo Karras asks. Medieval documents that have come down to us tell a great deal about the things that men did, but not enough about what they did specifically as men, or what these practices meant to them in terms of masculinity. Yet no less than in our own time, masculinity was a complicated construct in the Middle Ages.In Thou Art the Man, Karras focuses on one figure, King David, who was important in both Christian and Jewish medieval cultures, to show how he epitomized many and sometimes contradictory aspects of masculine identity. For late medieval Christians, he was one of the Nine Worthies, held up as a model of valor and virtue; for medieval Jews, he was the paradigmatic king, not just a remnant of the past, but part of a living heritage. In both traditions he was warrior, lover, and friend, founder of a dynasty and a sacred poet. But how could an exemplar of virtue also be a murderer and adulterer? How could a physical weakling be a great warrior? How could someone whose claim to the throne was not dynastic be a key symbol of the importance of dynasty? And how could someone who dances with slaves be noble?Exploring the different configurations of David in biblical and Talmudic commentaries, in Latin, Hebrew, and vernacular literatures across Europe, in liturgy, and in the visual arts, Thou Art the Man offers a rich case study of how ideas and ideals of masculinity could bend to support a variety of purposes within and across medieval cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMasculinityxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMasculinityxReligious aspectsxJudaismxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMasculinityzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aGender Studies.  aHistory.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073921340uhttps://www.degruyter